# Monday Error Handling

## Patterns to Flag

- Parsing `data` from GraphQL responses without checking `errors` (non-empty array means partial or full failure)
- Monday API calls not wrapped in `try`/`catch` or equivalent (unhandled rejections on network failures)
- Ignoring `status_code`, `error_message`, or top-level error fields when the client library exposes them
- Retry loops that do not treat HTTP 429 or rate-limit headers with backoff and jitter
- Heavy queries without reading or logging `complexity` fields when available (blind to budget exhaustion)

## What to Do

- After every request, if `errors` exists and has entries, branch on it; do not assume `data` is authoritative
- Wrap API calls in try/catch; map known Monday error shapes to user-visible or log messages
- On 429, honor `Retry-After` or exponential backoff; cap retries and surface permanent failures
- Include `complexity { before after reset_in_x_seconds }` in queries when debugging cost; monitor `after` approaching limits
- Log correlation IDs or request context when the API returns structured errors for support

## Exceptions

- Generated GraphQL types where a thin wrapper already centralizes error checks (flag only the wrapper if it omits checks)
- Mocked responses in unit tests that intentionally omit error paths
- One-off exploratory scripts with explicit "no production" comments and no persistence side effects
